dataIdInfo.idAbs:
Automatically generate a map of forested riparian buffers and their widths. Two output files are generated:

  1. A copy of the input hydrography, split into even intervals with a field indicating FRBWidth on either side.

  2. A shapefile containing transect rectangles along each interval of the hydrography, extending up to the width of the FRB, with a filed indicating the FRBWidth.

This tool works best with an accurate input hydrology dataset. Recommended:

  1. USGS NDHHydrography Flowline subset with "FType" = 460

  2. A high-resolution (1m) canopy cover map.

Adjusting the parameters will greatly influence the results. Please read the detailed description of each parameter.

Consts.useLimit: Use freely and share openly! Please credit the author if results are used in any final works.

tool.name: ForestedBuffer

param.name: out_folder
param.displayname: Intermediate Output Folder (Reuses files from here if available)
param.dialogReference:
An empty output folder to store results, or a folder containing partial results to continue processing.

If large areas are being processed, this tool will split the data into 10km x 10km zones for sequential processing. If for any reason the program is not able to complete, you can resume where you left off by indicating the folder that contains the partial results.

If resuming the tool, check to make sure prior outputs are acceptable before continuing, and delete any files that were corrupted.
param.pythonReference: An empty output folder to store results, or a folder containing partial results to continue processing.

param.name: in_hydro
param.dialogReference:
UTM projection required. This tool has not been tested with any other projection, and does not perform any internal reprojection.

The more accurate your input hydrology, the better results this tool will produce.

If the hydrology is offset from the true stream location, FRBWidth may be incorrectly calculated. See "Tolerated Distance" parameter for possible options to correct for inaccurate input data.

param.name: in_cover
param.dialogReference:
UTM projection required. This tool has not been tested with any other projection, and does not perform any internal reprojection.

The more accurate and precise your canopy cover map, the better results this tool will produce.

If you have a low resolution canopy cover map (eg. 30m), you mustincrease the Buffer Length, Buffer Slice Width, and Tolerated Distance parameters from the default.

A high-resolution (eg. 1m) canopy cover map must be used if you would like to determine FRBWidth within a 5m accuracy range.

param.name: transect_length
param.dialogReference:
The maximum buffer width to check. No FRBWidth will be marked as higher than this in the output, even though it may be wider.

A longer maximum buffer width will increase computation time.

This tool may overestimate FRBWidth whenever a second stream section intersects the first stream section's maximum buffer (usually at stream merges/splits), so it is recommended that you do not to set this value any higher than neccessary.
param.pythonReference: Use the smallest value neccessary to lower computation time and avoid overestimation.

param.name: transect_width
param.dialogReference:
Interval length to split the input hydrology data into. Smaller values increase computation time.

The tool declares an FRB ended whenever canopy cover is completely interrupted within a buffer slice.

A smaller value will produce more precise results, but may be too strict for certain uses.

A larger value (eg. 10m) will be more lenient about small gaps in the canopy cover within an FRB.
param.pythonReference: Interval length to split the input hydrology data into. Smaller values increase computation time.

param.name: tolerance
param.dialogReference:
Maximum distance from input hydrology that a buffer is allowed to begin at.

This value is used to allow some lee-way for inaccurate input hydrology data, and can correct for this up to a certain point.

This value is also used to define how close to the stream a buffer must be in order to be accepted as an FRB.

The two issues addressed by this tool are disjoint, and under certain circumstances it may be neccessary to split the original dataset into parts where differing values are required.
param.pythonReference: Maximum distance from hydrology that a buffer can begin at. Use to account for accuray issues of input hydrology data.

param.name: key_widths
param.dialogReference:
Space separated list of key FRBWidths to count and add as fields in split output hydrology.

For each entry, a field is added to the output hydrology, with a value (0,1,2) denoting how many of the buffers at that interval meet or exceed the key width.

Useful for quickly generating data and symbolizing output maps to show where target FRBWidths are being met.
param.pythonReference: Space separated list of key FRBWidths to count and add as fields in split output hydrology.

param.name: out_frb
param.dialogReference:
Output FRB feature.

Depending on the size of the input, this file may be very large and contain many polygons.

param.name: isDel
param.dialogReference:
Whether or not to delete partial files after completion.

It is recommended not to check this unless you are entirely satisfied with your results and plan to run a large automated process.

If you are manually reviewing your results, we recommend simply deleting any intermediate files once you are complete.

Intermediate files can also be helpful if you would like to change any step of the process yourself, as they can be input into other tools if desired.

param.name: reuseFiles
param.dialogReference:
If you are continuing a previously aborted process, leave this checked.

If you would like to overwrite past results in the output folder, uncheck.

Note that if you changed any parameters, but are attempting to continue a previous process, the results will not be consistent.
param.pythonReference: Overwrites any files in output folder if unchecked.

tool.usage:
Adjusting the parameters will greatly influence the results. Please read the detailed description of each parameter. If the recommended data sets are used, the default values will produce results acceptable for many use cases.

Setting smaller intervals will increase computation time, and increase precision of the output, but will also cause a stricter process to define the end of a buffer transect.
